TY  - JOUR
AB  - Mr. Snyder's conclusion that the concentration of wealth represents an improvement in well-being is based on the identification of well-being with industrial expansion. It further assumes that production can be expanded by reducing consumption. Over the short run the volume of saving is more dependent upon the level ofproduction than upon the concentration of income. Distribution must be analyzed in terms of rates+ADs- well-being is a matter of aggregate receipts. Against the familiar theoretical view that profits disappear under stable conditions, Mr. Snyder holds that +ACI-stable business means stable profits+ACI- large enough to finance the expansion of American industry on the scale it has grown to during the past concentration of wealth dictum neglects the requirements which modern industry imposes upon the worker. Poverty is a cause of unemployability. The author's claim for the rich assumes an unnecessary burden of apologetics+ADs- and although his facts indicate the irrelevance of much theory, the conclusions are strictly on the side of the angels.
AU  - Humphrey, Don D.
